userStories.description:
US-012 audit (commit `eb317143a`) flagged a panic-safety gap in `rivetkit-typescript/packages/rivetkit-napi/src/napi_actor_events.rs:1082-1092` (`with_dispatch_cancel_token`):

```rust
pub(crate) async fn with_dispatch_cancel_token<...>(...) -> Result<...> {
    let (cancel_id, cancel_token) = cancel_token::register_token();
    let result = dispatch(cancel_id).await;   // ← if this future panics,
                                               //   cancel_token::cancel(cancel_id) and
                                               //   cancel_token::drop_token(cancel_id)
                                               //   NEVER run. The token leaks in the
                                               //   static scc::HashMap forever.
    cancel_token::cancel(cancel_id);
    cancel_token::drop_token(cancel_id);
    result
}
```

If the inner dispatch future (an action handler, HTTP handler, etc.) panics, the cleanup lines never fire. Over time this leaks entries into the process-wide `scc::HashMap<u64, CancellationToken>` that backs `cancel_token::register_token`. Unbounded growth on a hot dispatch path = real memory leak.

Fix: wrap the dispatch in a drop-guard that runs cancel+drop during normal completion AND during panic unwind.
